<TITLE> Floods to worsen, head for Dhaka </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 6 (bdnews24.com)  The country's overall flood situation continued to deteriorate on Saturday with rivers still swelling, leaving hundreds of thousands of people and livestock in dire straits. The Flood Forecasting and Warning Centre said the low-lying areas in the central region of the country, including Dhaka, might see worse flooding in the next two to three days. It also forecast further flooding in the next two to three days in Madaripur, Faridpur, Munshiganj, Bogra, Jamalpur, Sirajganj, Tangail, Manikganj, Rajbari, Shaiatpur, Chandpur and Chapainawabganj. Countrywide, rivers rose at 30 points, decreased at 39 points and were flowing over danger levels at 24 points on Saturday compared to Friday, according to the FFWC. The flood forecast said that water levels of the Brahmaputra and Jamuna were still rising though the Padma river had started receding. The Jamuna was flowing 53 cm above the danger level at Sirajganj point, 39 cm above at Aricha and 19 cm above the danger mark at Bahadurabad point. The Padma was still flowing 96cm over the red mark at Bhagyakul point and 90 cm over at Gualunda point. Hundreds of thousands of marooned flood victims, meanwhile, are facing acute shortages of food and drinking water and say authorities are not doing enough with the relief. bdnews24.com/c
